Supplier discretion over provision: theory and an application to medical care.

Malcomson JM(1).

Author information:
(1)University of Oxford. james.malcomson@economics.oxford.ac.uk

Suppliers who are better informed than purchasers, such as physicians treating 
insured patients, often have discretion over what to provide. I show how, when 
the purchaser observes what is supplied but neither the recipient type nor the 
actual cost incurred, optimal provision differs from what would be efficient if 
the purchaser had full information, weather or not the supplier can extract 
informational rent. The analysis is applied to, among other things, data on 
tests for coronary artery disease and to Medicare diagnosis-related groups 
defined by the treatment given, not just the diagnosis, illustrating the biases 
in provision that result.

