837. Artif Organs. 2005 Dec;29(12):972-5. doi: 10.1111/j.1525-1594.2005.00171.x.

Valve replacement surgery in patients with end-stage renal disease: long-term 
results.

Gultekin B(1), Ozkan S, Uguz E, Atalay H, Akay T, Arslan A, Sezgin A, Ozdemir N, 
Tasdelen A, Aslamaci S.

Author information:
(1)Department of Cardiovascular Surgery, Baskent University, Ankara, Turkey. 
bahadirg2002@yahoo.com

BACKGROUND: The life expectancy of patients with chronic renal failure who are 
dependent on dialysis is very poor. This study was undertaken to determine 
time-related outcomes in dialysis patients requiring cardiac valve replacement.
METHODS: From 1994 to 2001, 29 end-stage renal disease (ESRD) patients on 
hemodialysis (HD) program underwent 30 valve replacement operations: 29 received 
mechanical valves (97%), and one received bioprosthetic valves. The sites of 
valve replacement were 11 aortic (36.7%), 18 mitral (60%), and one both aortic 
and mitral (3.3%). Mean age was 42.46 +/- 14.26 years (range 17-75 years). 
Follow-up was completed in 28 patients (96.5%).
RESULTS: Early postoperative mortality (in the first 30 days) was 3.4% (n = 1). 
The overall estimated Kaplan-Meier survival was 56.7% at 36 months, 46.7% at 60 
months, and 43.3% at 96 months. HD program was discontinued for two patients 
after renal transplantation in the follow-up period. All patients, except the 
one with bioprosthesis, used warfarin sodium for anticoagulation and none of 
them had bleeding. One of the patients had a major cerebrovascular accident 
(CVA) and another one had a minor CVA at the follow-up (6.7%).
CONCLUSIONS: Life quality is better and life expectancy is longer after valve 
replacement in ESRD patients who have valvular disease. Also, longer life 
expectancy increases the probability for finding donors for kidney 
transplantation.

